683
00:34:47,319 --> 00:34:49,254
for people could beat us up with.

684
00:34:49,254 --> 00:34:51,523
And then people picked 'em up and just beat us up with them.

685
00:34:51,523 --> 00:34:53,224
And we're like, huh, that was an interesting experiment.

686
00:34:53,224 --> 00:34:56,761
We probably shouldn't have given all those weapons to all the people who are mad.

687
00:34:56,761 --> 00:35:01,833
But, um, if that had not erupted at that moment, you know, maybe I would've thought--

688
00:35:01,833 --> 00:35:05,403
'Cause at the beginning, the transparency was nothing but, like,

689
00:35:05,403 --> 00:35:08,673
um, hugs and, uh, high-fives all around.

690
00:35:08,673 --> 00:35:12,544
Like, everybody at our-- you know, our PAX meetups, like, that was our community experience,

691
00:35:12,544 --> 00:35:15,413
was everyone just telling us how much they were excited about the game

692
00:35:15,413 --> 00:35:17,082
and how much they loved us and everything.

693
00:35:17,082 --> 00:35:23,088
And then when we announced the change in the schedule, just all that-- just people just--

694
00:35:23,088 --> 00:35:26,591
it seemed like there was a big crowd of people just ready to-- just really super mad.

695
00:35:26,591 --> 00:35:32,430
And if you Google, like, um, "'Broken Age,' broken promises" on the Internet-- which I do every night--

696
00:35:32,430 --> 00:35:34,499
if you Google that, you'll see all these angry articles.

697
00:35:34,499 --> 00:35:38,536
Not just from, like, random people on Twitter, but, like, these journalists who are like,

698
00:35:38,536 --> 00:35:42,207
"They really let everybody down with this and they should really be sorry."

699
00:35:42,207 --> 00:35:43,708
And, um...

700
00:35:43,708 --> 00:35:47,379
and here we are at the end and we're shipping the game and it took a long time,

701
00:35:47,379 --> 00:35:49,547
but it's everything we said we were gonna do.

702
00:35:49,547 --> 00:35:53,518
Uh...and I want to mail all those people individually and be like,

703
00:35:53,518 --> 00:35:56,988
"It's time for you to apologize about that article." But I don't think they feel like they were wrong.

704
00:35:56,988 --> 00:35:59,557
I think they feel like-- that we still really messed up.

705
00:35:59,557 --> 00:36:01,226
But, um, I don't.

706
00:36:01,226 --> 00:36:03,194
I feel like...

707
00:36:03,194 --> 00:36:05,296
I feel--isn't it great to know I've learned nothing?

708
00:36:05,296 --> 00:36:07,132
But I feel like...

709
00:36:07,380 --> 00:36:12,670
[Laughter] I feel, like, officially that--

710
00:36:12,670 --> 00:36:16,141
I feel like I just need to make an official announcement that I don't apologize for anything,

711
00:36:16,141 --> 00:36:18,043
because I feel really good about it.

712
00:36:18,043 --> 00:36:21,146
And if we had shipped one day earlier, the game would've been one day buggier.

713
00:36:21,146 --> 00:36:26,317
And, um, if we had shipped the game that the original $3.3 million paid for,

714
00:36:26,317 --> 00:36:27,619
it would've been small.

715
00:36:27,619 --> 00:36:31,122
And I like the game that we made instead, and we put a lot of our own money into it,

716
00:36:31,122 --> 00:36:33,291
and I think I'm really, really happy.

717
00:36:33,291 --> 00:36:37,595
This is the game, this is what the game kinda said that it wanted to be, about this size,

718
00:36:37,595 --> 00:36:39,030
and we did a really good version of it.

719
00:36:39,030 --> 00:36:41,666
And so I don't apologize for anything.

720
00:36:41,920 --> 00:37:38,857
[Music] Raz: He makes me laugh.

721
00:37:38,857 --> 00:37:42,360
"And that's why it's called a game." Schafer: Yay!

722
00:37:42,600 --> 00:37:49,134
[Applause] That's awesome.

723
00:37:49,134 --> 00:37:52,504
Uh, even though you like basketball...

724
00:37:52,504 --> 00:37:55,340
Burbank: We all have our faults.

725
00:37:55,340 --> 00:37:56,474
Schafer: That's awesome. Well, yes.

726
00:37:56,474 --> 00:37:57,642
Well, that's awesome.

727
00:37:57,642 --> 00:37:59,677
Now, uh, congratulations, Gabe.

728
00:37:59,677 --> 00:38:01,246
No speech?

729
00:38:01,246 --> 00:38:02,747
Gabe: No. Schafer: Okay.

730
00:38:04,382 --> 00:38:05,617
Oh...one more thing.

731
00:38:05,617 --> 00:38:09,087
We have boxes of "Broken Age," actual boxes of "Broken Age,"

732
00:38:09,087 --> 00:38:11,990
and we have enough for everyone here to get one!

733
00:38:11,990 --> 00:38:13,091
Ryken: It's under our seat?

734
00:38:13,091 --> 00:38:14,292
Schafer: What?

735
00:38:14,292 --> 00:38:15,827
Look under your seat...

736
00:38:15,827 --> 00:38:19,130
and that'll give me time to open this box.

737
00:38:19,130 --> 00:38:25,303
Offscreen: Now that this is wrapping up, like, how do you feel about the whole experience?

738
00:38:25,303 --> 00:38:30,742
Schafer: I wish I really knew right now if I could say 100% what I learned from all that.

739
00:38:30,742 --> 00:38:35,680
'Cause some of it's still, you know, uh, too soon.

740
00:38:35,680 --> 00:38:39,117
Like, uh, 'cause there's this part of me that's like, I just wanna not tell anybody

741
00:38:39,117 --> 00:38:40,385
about what we're working on right now.

742
00:38:40,385 --> 00:38:43,254
Like, I feel just kinda, like, so exposed that I just wanna be--

743
00:38:43,254 --> 00:38:47,759
I just wanna have some secrets for a little while, just as a kinda break from that.

744
00:38:47,759 --> 00:38:51,629
I had a pleasant trip down memory lane making an adventure game, but I remembered

745
00:38:51,629 --> 00:38:52,764
how hard they are to make.

746
00:38:52,764 --> 00:38:56,568
And, um, I don't think my next game will be an adventure game.

747
00:38:56,568 --> 00:38:58,736
I wouldn't say I'd never make one again.

748
00:38:58,736 --> 00:39:02,640
But in the end, I really-- I really think the team put together a beautiful game,

749
00:39:02,640 --> 00:39:05,076
and that's what I'm most happy with.

750
00:39:05,076 --> 00:39:06,344
'Kay.

751
00:39:06,344 --> 00:39:09,480
Now, this is gonna be awkward in case this came out wrong.

752
00:39:12,483 --> 00:39:14,586
This is a little light.

753
00:39:14,586 --> 00:39:15,687
That's a different game.

754
00:39:15,687 --> 00:39:17,322
What?

755
00:39:17,322 --> 00:39:21,693
Whoa, -look at that. -Beautiful.

756
00:39:21,693 --> 00:39:22,794
It looks beautiful, okay wait.

757
00:39:22,794 --> 00:39:24,162
I don't believe it.

758
00:39:24,162 --> 00:39:26,631
The design of this was supposed to have Vella on the bottom,

759
00:39:26,631 --> 00:39:28,600
'cause her hair is touching the logo.

760
00:39:28,600 --> 00:39:32,003
Not that I'm gonna complain, 'cause it's really awesome.

761
00:39:32,003 --> 00:39:33,671
Okay.

762
00:39:33,671 --> 00:39:35,306
I--I just have to demonstrate before you leave.

763
00:39:35,306 --> 00:39:36,441
This is fantastic.

764
00:39:36,441 --> 00:39:40,345
Let's see if it works; I've never tested this before.

765
00:39:40,345 --> 00:39:42,780
Gah, no, it doesn't work.

766
00:39:42,780 --> 00:39:44,148
Gah! Nope.

767
00:39:44,148 --> 00:39:46,651
Let's see, how does it actually--?

768
00:39:46,651 --> 00:39:49,320
Okay, get rid of this.

769
00:39:49,320 --> 00:39:51,522
Whoa...

770
00:39:51,522 --> 00:39:52,624
Very cool.

771
00:39:52,624 --> 00:39:53,491
And that, and that?

772
00:39:53,491 --> 00:39:54,592
See?

773
00:39:54,592 --> 00:39:56,227
And then, oh...

774
00:39:56,227 --> 00:40:00,331
I want everyone to do that when you get your copy and fix it, okay?

775
00:40:01,920 --> 00:40:08,673
[Applause] That is kinda funny, we did Kickstart this thing

776
00:40:08,673 --> 00:40:11,242
and now it's actually a box in my hand.

777
00:40:11,242 --> 00:40:12,844
Well, that pretty much ends this documentary.

778
00:40:12,844 --> 00:40:14,646
And...scene.

779
00:40:14,646 --> 00:40:17,548
I really hoped when it came out people wouldn't forget about

780
00:40:17,548 --> 00:40:19,584
how it was funded and just kinda talk about the game.

781
00:40:19,584 --> 00:40:22,320
But it seemed like every review had to talk about the development story,

782
00:40:22,320 --> 00:40:24,856
and so that was part of the lore for a long time, still.

783
00:40:24,856 --> 00:40:29,494
So I hope, um, five years from now when people talk about adventure games,

784
00:40:29,494 --> 00:40:31,229
they can look at it as just an adventure game.

785
00:40:31,229 --> 00:40:35,199
And so I think it'll be remembered well, and people can just kinda get over

786
00:40:35,199 --> 00:40:37,468
the crowdfunding part of it.

787
00:40:37,468 --> 00:40:42,473
Kipnis: I--to be honest with you, I'm not really sure how this whole thing is gonna be looked at in the end.

788
00:40:42,473 --> 00:40:44,842
Um...

789
00:40:44,842 --> 00:40:49,314
I--I guess, like, everyone has hopes for, like, a game when it comes out,

790
00:40:49,314 --> 00:40:53,451
and I had certain hopes that, um...

791
00:40:53,451 --> 00:40:55,820
maybe were not fulfilled, necessarily.

792
00:40:55,820 --> 00:41:02,827
And, uh, and it has more to do with just, like, I really hoped people would love the game.

793
00:41:02,827 --> 00:41:07,598
Um, and it's not to say that they didn't, but I kinda just, um--

794
00:41:07,598 --> 00:41:14,605
I think there--there was a lot of controversy surrounding the game and the company

795
00:41:14,605 --> 00:41:16,574
that I wish hadn't been there.

796
00:41:16,574 --> 00:41:20,611
Like, I just wish it was...

797
00:41:20,611 --> 00:41:21,579
I don't know.

798
00:41:21,579 --> 00:41:24,148
Annable: It was a long, hard road, and it was very public,

799
00:41:24,148 --> 00:41:27,218
and I feel like there were a lot of things that changed.

800
00:41:27,218 --> 00:41:32,991
Um, and they weren't necessarily just because of "Broken Age" and its visibility.

801
00:41:32,991 --> 00:41:37,795
I think the company is a different company now than it was three years ago,

802
00:41:37,795 --> 00:41:41,599
and I'm trying to still figure out, why?

803
00:41:41,599 --> 00:41:43,501
I don't know, are we just older?

804
00:41:43,501 --> 00:41:46,537
Offscreen: Do you have any expectation of "Broken Age's" performance?

805
00:41:46,537 --> 00:41:47,872
Annable: I don't know.

806
00:41:47,872 --> 00:41:51,376
Bailey: And then...uh, talking about sales of "Broken Age,"

807
00:41:51,376 --> 00:41:54,545
so, uh, sales on Steam, we had a feature spot.

808
00:41:54,545 --> 00:41:58,383
Um, it acted more like an update than, like, a--a new push.

809
00:41:58,383 --> 00:42:03,988
Um, however, we got a feature on Apple, which is doing really well; about $25,000 a day.

810
00:42:03,988 --> 00:42:09,160
Um, and then we also have, um, sales for, uh, Sony.

811
00:42:09,160 --> 00:42:12,563
PS4, we had, like, $100,000 worth of sales, uh, over the weekend.

812
00:42:12,563 --> 00:42:14,766
And it just got featured, so, uh, that's cool.

813
00:42:14,766 --> 00:42:17,769
Schafer: My expectation-- my expectation of "Broken Age" in the end

814
00:42:17,769 --> 00:42:19,570
would just be to break even.

815
00:42:19,570 --> 00:42:22,707
I know it was kind of always like a Kickstarter, like, you plan on it--

816
00:42:22,707 --> 00:42:27,612
Like, it's--the risk is gone of losing money on it, so you know you've broken even if you just make the game

817
00:42:27,612 --> 00:42:28,813
to that amount of money.

818
00:42:29,013 --> 00:42:32,583
But we made it, like, twice as much, almost, as we got in, or more.

819
00:42:32,583 --> 00:42:36,454
And so, um, we will just about make that back.

820
00:42:36,454 --> 00:42:40,358
And the biggest change is that we don't need the publishers anymore, 100%.

821
00:42:40,358 --> 00:42:43,795
You know, it used to be, like, there was no money in the world outside of publishers.

822
00:42:43,795 --> 00:42:45,596
And I think crowdfunding's here to stay.

823
00:42:45,596 --> 00:42:48,499
I think it's, um, hopefully gonna grow.

824
00:42:48,499 --> 00:42:52,770
And in my dream-- my dream world, it would be big enough to fund AAA games

825
00:42:52,770 --> 00:42:58,109
and it would be the way that we fund all games going forward.

826
00:42:58,109 --> 00:43:01,379
So now when we're talking to a publisher, the deals are better.

827
00:43:01,379 --> 00:43:04,849
We're asking for less money, but we're also not entirely dependent on them

828
00:43:04,849 --> 00:43:06,584
to make payroll next week.

829
00:43:06,584 --> 00:43:08,519
We're not like, "Please, we just--sign us.

830
00:43:08,519 --> 00:43:12,523
We'll--we'll sign anything, we just gotta make payroll." It's like, okay, you gotta kick us in the teeth

831
00:43:12,523 --> 00:43:14,358
once a month and all this stuff.

832
00:43:14,358 --> 00:43:17,662
And now we only have to take good deals with people we like.

833
00:43:17,662 --> 00:43:21,666
So we still work with publishers, but, um, it's different.

834
00:43:21,666 --> 00:43:24,502
Because we're 100% in control.

835
00:43:26,337 --> 00:43:27,872
Annable: Yeah, we're not...

836
00:43:27,872 --> 00:43:31,476
we're not rollin' in millions of dollars.

837
00:43:31,476 --> 00:43:35,880
I--I don't know if that would necessarily make us happier, though.

838
00:43:35,880 --> 00:43:38,483
Schafer: You guys are the best.

839
00:43:38,483 --> 00:43:40,485
Thank you for all your lovely audio.

840
00:43:40,485 --> 00:43:41,853
And thanks for your beard.

841
00:43:41,853 --> 00:43:43,488
Stoddard: It's kind of a milestone.

842
00:43:43,488 --> 00:43:50,127
I think there's a-- there's a few things in general around gaming that "Broken Age," like,

843
00:43:50,127 --> 00:43:54,499
really kinda did a push towards a new area.

844
00:43:54,499 --> 00:43:56,634
And I like that.

845
00:43:56,634 --> 00:43:59,871
Um, there's a whole bunch of stuff, like, we could've done differently

846
00:43:59,871 --> 00:44:02,473
and, like, we definitely fell down in some areas.

847
00:44:02,473 --> 00:44:04,308
But, like, so what?

848
00:44:04,308 --> 00:44:05,843
Like, that's how you-- that's how you go forward.

849
00:44:05,843 --> 00:44:10,014
Like, if you never fail, then you just aren't learning anything.

850
00:44:10,014 --> 00:44:13,284
You're just... being boring, really.

851
00:44:14,752 --> 00:44:16,554
Franzke: I think it was a huge success.

852
00:44:16,554 --> 00:44:19,290
Without this project, who knows?

853
00:44:19,290 --> 00:44:25,229
Maybe Kickstarter would have never been the prime platform for, you know, crowdfunded games.

854
00:44:25,229 --> 00:44:31,002
I think it made it possible for a lot of other people to--to work on their dream projects,

855
00:44:31,002 --> 00:44:33,404
so that's--that's pretty cool, yeah.

856
00:44:33,404 --> 00:44:36,474
So overall, you know, I couldn't be happier, I really couldn't.

857
00:44:36,474 --> 00:44:42,446
And, you know, the other day, um, the other day I went to just a random technology store

858
00:44:42,446 --> 00:44:46,017
here in Germany, and--and we just, um...

859
00:44:46,017 --> 00:44:48,252
walked by this little thing.

860
00:44:48,252 --> 00:44:54,258
So, just have--to see this physical manifestation of all the work that, you know,

861
00:44:54,258 --> 00:44:57,562
went into--into this game is, like, super awesome.

862
00:44:57,562 --> 00:45:00,231
Schafer: Hey, Ray! Good job. Crook: Has the soundtrack in there.

863
00:45:00,231 --> 00:45:02,199
Schafer: Oh, I forgot to mention, it has the soundtrack in there.

864
00:45:02,199 --> 00:45:05,503
Crook: I mean, I guess we did accomplish what we wanted to, which was to do this game.

865
00:45:05,503 --> 00:45:08,773
And we--and we did that, and we--and we finished it.

866
00:45:08,773 --> 00:45:14,612
I think what we did do that was the-- that I think was the most beneficial to everybody

867
00:45:14,612 --> 00:45:21,819
was that we kind of cracked things open and we let people look inside of how things work.

868
00:45:21,819 --> 00:45:28,492
And this maybe will help them to see how things-- uh, how difficult, uh, it is,

869
00:45:28,492 --> 00:45:32,496
and how we're kinda lucky that anything even comes out.

870
00:45:32,496 --> 00:45:36,467
Like, that any video games actually get finished, um, is kind of a miracle.

871
00:45:36,467 --> 00:45:37,501
And--and so that's good.

872
00:45:37,501 --> 00:45:39,804
I hope that-- that helps...

873
00:45:39,804 --> 00:45:44,208
I--I hope that helps people who are fans of video games and like playing video games,

874
00:45:44,208 --> 00:45:49,080
it just helps them understand and have a little bit of empathy towards, uh,

875
00:45:49,080 --> 00:45:51,616
those of us who are in this industry.

876
00:45:51,616 --> 00:45:57,855
Um...you know, we're lucky to be in it, and I--you know, I'm grateful to be in it, um,

877
00:45:57,855 --> 00:46:01,826
but it's not always easy, and--and it's-- and I'm glad that

878
00:46:01,826 --> 00:46:06,364
we were able to show that to people in--in an honest way, so it's kinda neat.

879
00:46:06,364 --> 00:46:12,403
I mean, if Double Fine's not around in 10 years, let's just, say, um-- it'll always be rem--

880
00:46:12,403 --> 00:46:13,804
like, it's out there now forever, right?

881
00:46:13,804 --> 00:46:17,208
Once it's on the Internet, um, it'll always be there.

882
00:46:17,208 --> 00:46:20,044
And so...so...

883
00:46:20,044 --> 00:46:23,614
Double Fine will always be...

884
00:46:23,614 --> 00:46:24,882
...around.

885
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:36,761
[Music] Stoddard: I think it was very positive.

886
00:46:36,761 --> 00:46:39,163
I think there was a lot of stuff that we really did contribute

887
00:46:39,163 --> 00:46:40,598
to the games industry.

888
00:46:40,598 --> 00:46:45,369
And...uh, and there's a lot of stuff that we sidestepped and, like, misstepped.

889
00:46:45,369 --> 00:46:47,405
And we're trying to learn from that, too.

890
00:46:47,405 --> 00:46:53,344
So, um, considering all that, I--going back and playing the actual game,

891
00:46:53,344 --> 00:46:55,346
I actually think we did really solid work.

892
00:46:55,346 --> 00:46:58,849
And I actually think it's, um...

893
00:46:58,849 --> 00:47:01,719
I think it's a really good game.

894
00:47:01,719 --> 00:47:05,189
I haven't really seen many reactions that are just blas.

895
00:47:05,189 --> 00:47:08,859
Like, it--it's usually a strong reaction, one way or the other.

896
00:47:08,859 --> 00:47:14,765
And to me, in any art form, that's great.

897
00:47:14,765 --> 00:47:18,202
Like, that means that it's provoking something.

898
00:47:18,202 --> 00:47:21,472
And I think that's what this is about.

899
00:47:21,472 --> 00:47:26,143
If, like, we did three years of work and there was all these trials and tribulations

900
00:47:26,143 --> 00:47:30,815
and at the end somebody just went, "Meh," like, that would be crushing!

901
00:47:30,815 --> 00:47:33,150
But it hasn't been like that; it's been the opposite.

902
00:47:33,150 --> 00:47:38,556
Like, it's either really, really good or really, really awful or, you know,

903
00:47:38,556 --> 00:47:41,592
very, very vocal, no matter what.

904
00:47:42,593 --> 00:47:43,761
Great.

905
00:47:43,761 --> 00:47:45,796
Then we did our job.

906
00:47:47,520 --> 00:49:42,200
[Music]

